{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem is a Trie-based optimization problem. To prevent identity theft, no ID can be a prefix of another. This is equivalent to ensuring that in a Trie containing all final IDs, every leaf node represents exactly one cow and no internal node represents a cow. The cost is the number of bits added to make each original string a unique leaf in a Trie where no original string is an ancestor of another.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "trie_construction_expert",
      "instructions": "Construct a Trie from the given N bitstrings. For each node in the Trie, track whether it is the end of an original ID and how many original IDs pass through or end at this node. Identify the structure of the tree where nodes are prefixes."
    },
    {
      "label": "greedy_cost_optimizer",
      "instructions": "Given the Trie structure, calculate the minimum bits to add. For any node that is marked as an end-of-ID, if it has descendants that are also end-of-ID, we must extend the current ID to a leaf. However, the problem asks for the minimum total bits such that no ID is a prefix of another. This is equivalent to ensuring that for every node that is an end-of-ID, it has no descendants that are also end-of-ID. If a node is an end-of-ID and has children, we must push the 'end-of-ID' status down to a leaf or add bits to the existing IDs to make them unique. Specifically, for each node that is an end-of-ID, if it has children, we must add bits to the current ID to make it a leaf that is not a prefix of any other. Actually, the rule is: no cow's reported prefix can be the full ID of another. This means no ID can be a prefix of another. Calculate the minimum bits to add to each string such that no string is a prefix of another, using a greedy approach on the Trie: for each node that is an end-of-ID, if it has children, we must extend it. The cost is the sum of (depth of leaf - depth of original ID) for all cows."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "The parent will combine the Trie structure and the greedy logic. The core logic is: 1. Build a Trie of all IDs. 2. For every node that represents an original ID, if that node has any descendants that are also original IDs (or if we need to separate them), we must ensure the current ID is extended. However, the problem is simpler: we need to ensure no ID is a prefix of another. In a Trie, this means no 'end-of-ID' node can be an ancestor of another 'end-of-ID' node. To minimize bits, for every 'end-of-ID' node that has descendants, we must extend it to a leaf. But we can also extend the descendants. The optimal strategy is to process the Trie bottom-up or top-down to ensure that every 'end-of-ID' node is a leaf. The total cost is the sum of bits added to each string."
}

